org.wikipedia
Class MBot

java.lang.Object
  org.wikipedia.MBot

public class MBot
extends java.lang.Object

Class consisting of stand-alone, multi-threaded bot methods. These methods are designed to get the specified task done, as damn fast as possible. Currently consists of an Upload and Deletion bot. You may wish to adjust adjust heap space according to the method you're running (Uploads may require more space depending on the size of files you're uploading and how many threads you've chosen to instantiate). Make feature requests here (fast) or on the project's Google Code issue tracker (slow).

See Also:
Fbot, FbotUtil, FbotParse
Author:
Fastily

Constructor that creates an MBot object.

Parameters:
user - The username to use
px - The password to use (This is not saved anywhere once the constructor exits)
domain - The domain to use (e.g. "commons.wikimedia.org", "en.wikipedia.org")
instances - The maximum number of threads to create when performing the requested action. Note that if instances > list.length, instances will be set to list.length. This is done for efficiency reasons. Remember, you need to adjust your heap space accordingly for the task at hand and for the number of threads lest you should get out of memory exceptions!
list - The list we'll be acting upon
reason - The reason(s) to use when performing the specified actions.
Throws:
javax.security.auth.login.FailedLoginException - If the login credentials you used were invalid.
java.io.IOException - If we encountered a network error.

setInstances

public void setInstances(java.lang.String user,
                         char[] px,
                         java.lang.String domain,
                         int instances)
                  throws java.io.IOException,
                         javax.security.auth.login.FailedLoginException
Hard sets the number of Wiki objects (instances) used by this MBot object. The only reason you should be calling this method is if you are planning on working on a larger data set but wish to retain the settings of the original MBot. This method is provided for convenience only; it's a better idea to create a new MBot object.

Parameters:
user - The username to use with these Wiki objects
px - The password to use with these Wiki objects
domain - The domain to use with these Wiki objects
instances - The number of instances to hard set the MBot object to use. Note that you may not reduce the number of Wiki objects, only increase.
Throws:
java.io.IOException - If we encountered a network error
javax.security.auth.login.FailedLoginException - If login credentials do not match/exist.
See Also:
setList(String[])

upload

public void upload()
Uploads files specified in the constructor. Interprets the list param in the constructor as a list of file paths and attempts to upload them to the specified Wiki with the specified credentials. Only the first reason param shall be interpreted as the text of the file description page; if you include more than one reason, the rest will be ignored Files will be uploaded using their default, system names. If an upload of a particular file fails for whatever reason, a stack trace shall be printed and uploading of the file shall be skipped.

Throws:
java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - If you did not specify at least one reason in the constructor.

addText

public void addText()
Adds text to the beginning of each page specified in the list param in the constructor. You MUST have two Strings in the reason param of the constructor. The first param shall be interpreted as the edit summary to use for each edit and the second param shall be interpreted as the text to add! If you specify more than two params, the rest shall be ignored. If an exception occurs when editing, that page will be skipped over.

Throws:
java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - If you did not specify at least two reasons in the constructor.

delete

public void delete()
Deletes files specified in the constructor. Interprets the list param in the constructor as a list of wiki pages and attempts to delete them from the specified Wiki with the specified credentials. Only the first reason param shall be interpreted as the rationale to use when deleting the file; if you include more than one reason, the rest will be ignored.

CAVEAT: If a deletion of a particular file fails for whatever reason, a stack trace, the method will continue to try and delete the page until the page is deleted. This means that if you're blocked or do not have the proper userrights associated with the account you're using to perform said action, the program will loop endlessly.

Throws:
java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - If you did not specify at least one reason in the constructor.
